C. Code-Level Fixes
C1. SQL Injection in Live Monitor (P0)
File: sections/live_monitor.py:112
PYTHON
# BEFORE (vulnerable):
st_clause = f"AND execution_status = '{status_filter}'" if status_filter != "ALL" else ""

# AFTER (safe):
st_clause = f"AND execution_status = {sql_literal(status_filter, 40)}" if status_filter != "ALL" else ""
C2. Live Monitor Fragment Should Use Cached Runner (P0)
File: sections/live_monitor.py — inside _live_panel(), replace raw session.sql() calls with run_query(..., tier="live") which already has 30s TTL caching.
C3. Global Date Range Cap (P1)
File: app.py or wherever global_start_date/global_end_date are set — add:
PYTHON
from datetime import date, timedelta
MAX_LOOKBACK_DAYS = 90

if st.session_state.get("global_start_date"):
    earliest_allowed = date.today() - timedelta(days=MAX_LOOKBACK_DAYS)
    if st.session_state["global_start_date"] < earliest_allowed:
        st.session_state["global_start_date"] = earliest_allowed
        st.warning(f"Date range capped to {MAX_LOOKBACK_DAYS} days to control query costs.")
C4. Narrow Cache Context (P1)
File: utils/query.py:575-589
PYTHON
def _cache_context() -> str:
    # Only include stable identity keys in context.
    # Per-query filter values should be part of the SQL text itself.
    return "|".join([
        str(st.session_state.get("active_company", "")),
        str(st.session_state.get("global_environment", "")),
        str(st.session_state.get("_overwatch_current_role", "")),
    ])
This prevents filter changes (warehouse, user, date) from invalidating unrelated cached queries. The SQL text already contains these filters, so the cache key (which includes the SQL hash) is naturally distinct.
